WEBVTT

00:03.621 --> 00:08.257
♪ ♪

00:08.492 --> 00:11.560
WILL SMITH: I'm gonna
tell you about the
most incredible place.

00:14.598 --> 00:17.966
It might be the weirdest
place in the whole universe...

00:19.837 --> 00:25.374
Full of liquid rock, crystal
caves and alien landscapes...

00:29.280 --> 00:31.580
And you know what?

00:32.183 --> 00:34.850
You're walking on it.

00:43.327 --> 00:47.963
We think we know our home,
but once you've seen it
from space it hits you...

00:51.168 --> 00:55.070
CHRIS: I really wish
that everyone could see the
world the way that I've had

00:55.172 --> 00:57.639
a chance to see it.

00:57.742 --> 01:01.577
NICOLE: First you look at it
and really are wondering what
it even is that you're seeing.

01:04.882 --> 01:07.883
-Just like I lived
my whole live in a semi
dark room and somebody

01:07.985 --> 01:10.452
flipped on the lights.

01:10.554 --> 01:13.555
MAE: A living, breathing,
working planet.

01:14.492 --> 01:19.161
-It's all just
so wonderfully unlikely,
and yet it's here.

01:23.501 --> 01:26.769
WILL SMITH: Eight
astronauts, with over 1,000
days in space between them,

01:27.938 --> 01:30.139
can tell us how
being up there...

01:30.241 --> 01:34.376
Helped them to truly
understand what
goes on down here.

01:36.247 --> 01:38.380
The weird connections.

01:39.183 --> 01:41.016
The near misses.

01:41.619 --> 01:44.019
The lucky breaks.

01:44.388 --> 01:47.422
That built our amazing world.

01:56.767 --> 02:02.371
The strangest place in
the whole universe might
just be right here.

02:16.387 --> 02:18.420
Oh, you ready
this morning, huh?

02:18.522 --> 02:19.521
Here you go.

02:19.623 --> 02:22.057
Let's have some fun.

02:22.159 --> 02:23.826
There you go.

02:23.928 --> 02:25.661
We take Earth for granted.

02:25.763 --> 02:27.296
Come on, come on.

02:27.398 --> 02:28.497
Come on.

02:28.599 --> 02:30.599
We take so much for granted.

02:30.701 --> 02:32.434
Hey, come on.

02:34.471 --> 02:36.205
In fact, there's one thing
that comes so naturally we
don't even think about it.

02:38.576 --> 02:40.542
Breathing.

02:41.045 --> 02:42.144
Yes, come on.

02:42.246 --> 02:44.146
Come on, come on.

02:46.217 --> 02:50.519
But if you knew even
half of what it takes to
make the oxygen we need,

02:52.289 --> 02:54.356
it would take
your breath away.

02:58.796 --> 03:00.762
You wanna know
about breathing?

03:00.865 --> 03:03.332
Ask this guy.

03:07.304 --> 03:12.274
-My first spacewalk,
holding on to the
outside of the spaceship,

03:15.112 --> 03:18.847
with nothing except the
sound of my own breathing.

03:23.020 --> 03:28.423
In my one hand is my entire
link with my own history.

03:31.695 --> 03:35.664
Everything that's human, every
story that's going on down
on the surface of the world,

03:36.901 --> 03:41.136
everybody I've ever met,
with the whole universe
in the other direction.

03:45.876 --> 03:48.677
And then...

03:48.979 --> 03:51.847
I let go.

03:53.150 --> 03:57.119
That's when you really
appreciate the significance

03:57.221 --> 04:00.489
of that thin blue line.

04:06.597 --> 04:10.365
It contains everything
that's important to us.

04:11.335 --> 04:14.002
It contains life.

04:18.175 --> 04:22.477
And then Houston called to
get back to work, I grabbed
back onto the handrail

04:22.579 --> 04:25.380
but while I
was working, suddenly...

04:27.084 --> 04:30.419
I had a searing
pain in my left eye.

04:31.755 --> 04:34.222
Like somebody had
just stabbed me.

04:34.325 --> 04:37.693
My eye just snapped shut
and it started tearing up.

04:38.729 --> 04:43.265
But the trouble is, without
gravity tears don't fall.

04:46.103 --> 04:49.137
The tear just gets
bigger and bigger.

04:51.141 --> 04:56.812
It got big enough that
it became a little lake of
water that went across the

04:56.914 --> 04:59.014
bridge of my nose...

04:59.116 --> 05:01.383
Into my other eye.

05:02.886 --> 05:06.188
So I call down to
Houston, "Houston, I'm
having a problem here.

05:06.924 --> 05:07.889
I can't see.

05:07.992 --> 05:10.258
I'm blinded in both eyes."

05:10.361 --> 05:12.694
"What did
he just say?
He's blind?"

05:12.930 --> 05:16.198
Houston looked at
what all the symptoms
were and said...

05:16.300 --> 05:19.735
"Maybe it's the
worst-case problem.

05:21.038 --> 05:24.639
You may have contamination
in your suit."

05:25.809 --> 05:28.777
"And you're gonna
have to flush it out."

05:30.414 --> 05:35.617
I reached up, turned
this little valve, popped
it and suddenly could hear,

05:36.754 --> 05:39.788
"Ssssss, sssss".

05:41.759 --> 05:47.729
As my precious supply
of oxygen hissed out into
the empty vacuum of space.

05:50.134 --> 05:56.271
(heart monitor beeping)

06:08.352 --> 06:10.585
(baby crying)

06:10.687 --> 06:13.955
There is nothing more
natural than breathing.

06:17.561 --> 06:21.496
Yet as far as we know,
this is the only planet
where that happens.

06:24.735 --> 06:28.370
The only planet with an
oxygen-rich environment.

06:29.540 --> 06:33.708
Without that, life
would be something
very different indeed.

06:49.226 --> 06:54.863
♪ ♪

07:18.956 --> 07:23.925
WILL SMITH: This is
Felipe's favorite place.

07:24.027 --> 07:27.529
Even though the air is toxic.

07:27.764 --> 07:32.567
The ground spits acid, and
there is no fresh water.

07:34.938 --> 07:37.139
No birds sing here.

07:37.241 --> 07:39.674
No insects fly.

07:39.776 --> 07:41.610
No plants grow.

08:07.070 --> 08:10.205
WILL SMITH: It's hard
to imagine anywhere
less inviting...

08:12.776 --> 08:17.212
But Felipe has found
one thing that calls
this hellhole home.

08:21.985 --> 08:25.153
And it doesn't use oxygen.

08:30.527 --> 08:34.129
It lives in a lake of acid.

08:43.273 --> 08:47.275
♪ ♪

08:55.085 --> 08:56.918
♪ ♪

09:31.955 --> 09:35.624
-It's hard to
imagine sometimes just how
important oxygen is to us,

09:36.593 --> 09:39.861
as the way to release energy.

09:41.531 --> 09:45.600
Every time I breathe
in, oxygen-rich air mixes
with the food I've eaten

09:47.170 --> 09:49.638
and creates energy.

09:49.740 --> 09:53.708
Power that enables
larger, more complex
creatures to exist.

10:03.053 --> 10:07.589
WILL SMITH: Our planet is
literally bursting with life,
so how on earth is there

10:07.691 --> 10:10.525
enough oxygen for everyone?

10:10.994 --> 10:14.029
The answer takes in some
pretty surprising stuff.

10:15.299 --> 10:20.201
Giant dust storms,
tiny snowflakes,
flying rivers;

10:21.738 --> 10:25.707
and the most important living
thing you've never heard of.

10:28.712 --> 10:32.080
But it begins in a desert.

10:35.252 --> 10:38.787
A desert made of salt.

10:48.865 --> 10:53.968
♪ ♪

11:02.913 --> 11:07.982
(chopping)

11:15.759 --> 11:18.927
(speaking in native language)

11:59.136 --> 12:02.871
WILL SMITH: The people
here rely on this
desert and so do we.

12:08.145 --> 12:11.379
But not because of the salt.

12:14.451 --> 12:19.854
(wind)

12:30.967 --> 12:37.038
♪ ♪

12:48.852 --> 12:51.953
JEFF: Dust storms can
be pretty amazing when
you see them from space.

12:52.456 --> 12:54.889
And sometimes they're huge.

12:54.991 --> 12:58.159
JERRY: You know, I had seen
little dust storms blowing
and you kinda look hard.

12:58.261 --> 13:00.161
This you didn't
need to look hard.

13:00.263 --> 13:06.034
It was a continent
of Northern Africa basically
obscured by thick brown dust.

13:07.204 --> 13:10.238
And as I orbited, I
couldn't wait to come back.

13:11.241 --> 13:14.509
And then when I did,
I saw that dust storm
that was over Africa now

13:14.611 --> 13:18.046
over the Atlantic Ocean.

13:19.950 --> 13:23.351
And my next orbit
I see it hitting the
coast of South America.

13:41.571 --> 13:46.808
-Every year about
27 million tons of that
African dust we can see

13:46.910 --> 13:52.647
from orbit drops out of the
sky into the Amazon Basin.

13:54.451 --> 13:56.951
And it turns out,
it's the perfect fertilizer.

14:07.497 --> 14:13.434
♪ ♪

14:17.807 --> 14:23.811
And as they grow, the
plants and the trees turn
carbon dioxide into oxygen.

14:33.990 --> 14:39.327
One single tree can
produce enough oxygen
to support two people.

14:39.629 --> 14:42.864
And the Amazon Rainforest...

14:42.966 --> 14:46.935
Is ten times the size of Texas,

14:47.804 --> 14:51.372
producing 20 times
more oxygen than all the

14:51.474 --> 14:55.376
people on the surface of the
Earth could consume.

14:57.514 --> 15:01.549
But, not one breath of
it leaves the Amazon.

15:19.069 --> 15:24.572
There are so many animals
living in the Amazon Basin
that the life there uses all

15:24.674 --> 15:27.075
that oxygen up.

15:31.181 --> 15:35.083
WILL SMITH: For all these
years I've been thinking
the rainforest is the lungs

15:35.185 --> 15:37.885
of the planet.

15:39.022 --> 15:43.024
Now sure, it makes a lot of
oxygen, but it uses it all.

15:45.395 --> 15:51.099
The rainforest does
help us breathe, but
not because of air.

15:51.835 --> 15:56.337
There's a river in the
Amazon, no, not that one,
there's another river,

15:57.774 --> 15:59.440
a river in the sky.

16:14.071 --> 16:17.205
WILL SMITH: For the most
part, I know this world from
standing on its surface.

16:19.877 --> 16:22.978
I mean, I've been
up to the top of the
Empire State Building,

16:23.080 --> 16:27.516
put my quarter in the scope,
and I've even jumped out
of planes a couple times.

16:30.721 --> 16:33.055
But that's nothing.

16:33.290 --> 16:38.293
The International
Space Station clocks
in at 1 million feet.

16:47.071 --> 16:51.239
CHRIS: Whenever there's a
free moment on the spaceship,
we try and get to the window

16:51.675 --> 16:53.408
to take pictures.

16:53.510 --> 16:57.946
And during my three
space flights, I took
about 45,000 photographs.

17:04.722 --> 17:07.823
And some parts of
the world are easy to
take pictures of...

17:09.159 --> 17:11.827
Like the outback of Australia.

17:12.129 --> 17:14.663
It's always a sunny day there.

17:14.765 --> 17:18.500
But there are parts of the
world that you almost never
get a good picture of.

17:21.004 --> 17:23.638
One of those is
the Amazon Basin.

17:23.741 --> 17:26.374
So it makes ya think...

17:26.477 --> 17:29.311
What's going on down there?

17:39.256 --> 17:44.259
♪ ♪

17:59.109 --> 18:03.011
WILL SMITH: For the last
ten years, Rosa has been
working in the Amazon,

18:03.514 --> 18:08.383
uncovering the surprising
way the rainforest helps
the whole planet breathe.

18:51.228 --> 18:54.563
WILL SMITH: She's not
kidding about special.

18:59.002 --> 19:03.038
This is the tallest structure
in all South America.

19:11.748 --> 19:15.517
Rosa has tried to climb
this tower twice before,

19:15.619 --> 19:17.853
but she's never
made it to the top.

20:00.898 --> 20:07.235
♪ ♪

20:17.948 --> 20:20.582
♪ ♪

20:20.684 --> 20:25.086
WILL SMITH: Now that's
a pretty cool climb, but
something else is rising too.

20:34.898 --> 20:39.401
If you could look
inside the trees...

20:39.503 --> 20:44.639
You'd see water sucked
up from the forest floor.

20:54.518 --> 20:59.554
♪ ♪

21:09.633 --> 21:14.469
♪ ♪

21:24.381 --> 21:28.950
♪ ♪

21:29.219 --> 21:32.854
When the water hits the
top, the combination
of sun and wind...

21:34.992 --> 21:38.026
Turns it into a mighty river.

21:39.096 --> 21:42.263
A flying river.

22:12.796 --> 22:15.530
CHRIS: This river of cloud
flows across South America,

22:16.800 --> 22:19.868
obscuring everything
beneath it...

22:23.774 --> 22:26.574
Until it runs
into a brick wall.

22:28.879 --> 22:32.747
5,500 miles long and
up to 4 miles high.

22:34.451 --> 22:36.484
The Andes.

22:39.222 --> 22:43.992
The clouds condense
into raindrops, which
then race down the slopes and

22:44.094 --> 22:48.129
flow directly back into
the Amazon Basin...

22:52.269 --> 22:56.004
Eroding the rock and
turning it into sediment...

22:58.008 --> 23:03.344
Until all those nutrients
are dumped into the ocean
and a whole other world.

23:26.136 --> 23:29.204
And waiting for
those sediments is an
extraordinary organism,

23:30.607 --> 23:32.440
four times thinner
than a human hair.

23:35.045 --> 23:37.312
It's called a diatom.

23:47.557 --> 23:51.793
Diatoms are the secret to
the Earth's oxygen supply.

23:55.532 --> 24:00.768
They use silica from
the ground up rock
to create new shells,

24:00.871 --> 24:04.472
which allows them
to reproduce.

24:05.408 --> 24:08.676
Their population
doubles every day...

24:09.980 --> 24:13.515
And they begin to
photosynthesize...

24:14.751 --> 24:19.354
Each one starting
to produce oxygen.

24:21.858 --> 24:23.591
WILL SMITH: Take a breath.

24:24.361 --> 24:26.427
Now take another.

24:26.763 --> 24:28.596
Now think about this:

24:28.698 --> 24:31.833
one of those breaths
was entirely provided by

24:31.935 --> 24:35.403
those little fellas
under the sea.

24:38.275 --> 24:43.778
-Looking at the oceans
from space, sometimes you
see a local area that's

24:43.880 --> 24:46.814
an entirely different color.

24:46.917 --> 24:50.351
And amazingly enough,
what you're looking at
is microscopic life.

24:52.822 --> 24:57.892
Diatom blooms that reflect
the light differently, so
that they show up from space.

25:00.630 --> 25:02.897
JEFF: Biggest one I think
I ever saw was huge.

25:04.100 --> 25:06.301
It covered hundreds of miles.

25:06.636 --> 25:08.102
JERRY: You know,
when you swim in the ocean

25:08.205 --> 25:10.171
you don't notice
the diatoms around you.

25:10.273 --> 25:13.908
But when you're
in space, you see the
vibrant colors of life.

25:16.146 --> 25:19.514
NICOLE: It's just so stunning,
the blues and the greens.

25:19.616 --> 25:24.085
But also, like, wow, those
things are keeping us alive.

25:27.924 --> 25:29.791
WILL SMITH: But you know what?

25:29.893 --> 25:33.328
Diatoms are important not
just because of what they
do when they're alive,

25:33.997 --> 25:36.764
but also what they
do once they're dead.

25:47.696 --> 25:50.464
CHRIS: I spent 166
days off the world.

25:52.334 --> 25:56.203
Underneath you,
the planet is silently,

25:56.305 --> 25:58.238
intimately revealing
itself to you,

25:58.541 --> 26:01.608
more and more,
every single time around.

26:03.979 --> 26:08.482
And from a spaceship, Earth
is definitely the Blue Planet.

26:12.221 --> 26:15.189
And pretty much
everywhere that there's
water, there's diatoms.

26:17.560 --> 26:20.661
There are trillions
of them in every ocean,

26:21.931 --> 26:25.165
and they can't all
rely on flying rivers.

26:26.869 --> 26:31.839
So diatoms around the world
have to get their nutrients
in different ways.

26:33.242 --> 26:37.044
Some about as far away
from tropical rainforests
as you can get.

26:50.059 --> 26:52.192
<i>HEIDI (over radio):</i>
<i>Okay guys, off you go.</i>

27:02.938 --> 27:05.372
Okay, yeah, slow down...

27:10.646 --> 27:12.779
You can stop right there, yeah.

27:21.223 --> 27:22.823
(inaudible)

27:23.092 --> 27:25.292
<i>MAN (over radio): Okay.</i>

27:25.394 --> 27:27.728
WILL SMITH: These
glaciers are unusual.

27:27.830 --> 27:30.163
They can slide
in sudden spurts.

27:31.200 --> 27:36.436
Still too slow
to see in real time, but
fast enough to hear...

27:38.741 --> 27:41.108
if you know how to listen.

27:44.413 --> 27:47.781
(low frequency rumble)

27:50.653 --> 27:55.489
Sometimes they move
300 times faster than
their normal glacial pace.

27:59.094 --> 28:03.664
Heidi can hear them crushing
a huge amount of rock,
as they grind their way

28:03.766 --> 28:06.266
down the valley.

28:08.170 --> 28:12.472
And when ice meets sea,
it makes a familiar sound.

28:38.167 --> 28:41.335
WILL SMTH: The popping
is a heads up for the team.

28:41.737 --> 28:44.104
The ice face is
about to crash.

28:44.707 --> 28:47.074
(bubbles popping)

28:47.176 --> 28:50.377
HEIDI: I'm hearing
increased activity, you
need to come back, okay?

29:16.572 --> 29:19.640
(bubbles popping)

29:36.959 --> 29:38.592
Wow!

29:45.801 --> 29:48.969
♪ ♪

29:49.338 --> 29:53.440
WILL SMITH: Diatom
dinner time.

29:54.777 --> 29:58.645
Now sometimes these
glaciers move really fast,
dumping tons and tons of

29:58.747 --> 30:01.481
nutrients into the sea.

30:01.583 --> 30:03.817
Boom!

30:04.286 --> 30:07.087
Sparking a feeding frenzy
and a population explosion.

30:12.327 --> 30:17.431
But then, just as
quickly as it started,
dinner time is over.

30:19.101 --> 30:24.671
The glaciers come to a
grinding halt and lie dormant,
sometimes for decades.

30:25.574 --> 30:28.008
Boom becomes bust.

30:34.983 --> 30:39.352
-When the nutrients run
out, the blooms fade and
most of the diatoms die.

30:46.495 --> 30:50.464
Their carcasses slowly
fall to the ocean floor...

30:52.434 --> 30:56.603
Where they carpet it in a
layer half a mile thick.

30:58.207 --> 31:01.441
We call it 'marine
snow', and that's exactly
what it looks like.

31:03.512 --> 31:05.846
Snowflakes.

31:07.983 --> 31:10.550
But unlike snowflakes,

31:10.652 --> 31:16.389
they never melt and
over millions of
years the sea beds rise...

31:19.294 --> 31:24.297
The ocean levels fall
and the ocean floor
becomes a salty desert.

31:30.172 --> 31:34.040
The desert that blows all
the way to the Amazon...

31:35.811 --> 31:38.111
That was once a sea bed.

31:38.213 --> 31:41.281
And the dust that makes
the rainforest grow?

31:43.519 --> 31:46.286
Diatom shells.

31:50.793 --> 31:54.494
It just goes to show how
incredibly interlinked
everything is.

31:57.533 --> 32:01.368
-There is absolutely nothing
on one side of the planet
that isn't connected in

32:01.470 --> 32:04.137
some way with the other
side of the planet.

32:08.577 --> 32:12.979
MAE: It's astounding how
all the systems down there
must work together in order

32:13.081 --> 32:15.315
for us to breathe.

32:22.357 --> 32:24.991
WILL SMITH: Which is great...

32:25.360 --> 32:28.228
But you only have to mess
with oxygen a little bit

32:28.330 --> 32:31.331
for things to start
going really wrong.

32:34.628 --> 32:38.564
ee, two, one.

32:39.133 --> 32:42.134
Lift off, lift off.

32:44.071 --> 32:50.209
♪ CHRIS: Though I've
flow 100,000 miles,
I'm feeling very still. ♪

32:53.848 --> 32:59.685
♪ Planet Earth is blue and
there's nothing left to do. ♪♪

33:10.231 --> 33:13.999
I love the fact that the
Earth has a blue sky.

33:18.205 --> 33:21.507
You can look up
and all of the various
shades of it, you know,

33:21.775 --> 33:23.909
the deepness of it and
the way the colors change

33:24.011 --> 33:29.848
close to the horizon
and that's everything
that we breathe,

33:29.950 --> 33:33.185
and keeps us alive.

33:33.287 --> 33:37.823
And you sort of fool
yourself into thinking,
it's really, really deep.

33:37.925 --> 33:41.026
Like it goes on
sort of forever.

33:44.298 --> 33:48.267
But when you're on
board a spaceship and
you look straight down,

33:50.204 --> 33:53.238
you hardly see the
atmosphere at all.

33:54.041 --> 33:58.343
It's only when you look
to the horizon that you
can see just how thin our

33:58.445 --> 34:01.513
atmosphere truly is.

34:01.615 --> 34:06.785
The thinnest of
delicate blue lines.

34:07.321 --> 34:11.823
It's because the gravity of
the Earth is pulling every
single one of those air

34:11.926 --> 34:16.228
molecules and pressing
it against the ground.

34:16.330 --> 34:20.198
But the further up you
go, the thinner it gets.

34:20.834 --> 34:25.504
It's sort of like if you
pluck a string on a guitar...

34:26.140 --> 34:28.607
When does the note stop?

34:29.410 --> 34:32.144
And our atmosphere is
like that guitar string.

34:32.947 --> 34:35.480
It just gets less and
less the higher you go.

34:38.586 --> 34:42.187
But what's surprising is,
how fast that happens.

34:43.757 --> 34:49.261
That blue line is so thin
that you can walk to where
the oxygen starts to run out.

34:59.540 --> 35:05.377
♪ ♪

35:14.655 --> 35:20.859
♪ ♪

35:22.896 --> 35:29.167
WILL SMITH: Being a doctor
in La Rinconada means that
you have 25,000 patients,

35:31.305 --> 35:34.873
living year-round in a town
as high as Everest base-camp.

36:17.584 --> 36:23.088
WILL SMITH: When Spanish
settlers first arrived here,
the lack of oxygen killed many

36:23.757 --> 36:27.059
of their babies at birth.

36:35.302 --> 36:38.937
Yet, people still live here.

36:40.274 --> 36:43.475
They still work here.

36:44.278 --> 36:49.047
Because in these mountains,
there's something that's
lured people through history.

36:59.526 --> 37:03.228
The promise of gold.

37:12.139 --> 37:14.639
This is the limit though.

37:14.742 --> 37:18.877
Humans can't live any higher.

37:23.083 --> 37:26.485
CHRIS: Without enough
oxygen, our organs can
start shutting down...

37:29.356 --> 37:33.125
And it can happen
surprisingly quickly.

37:34.194 --> 37:39.264
So astronauts actually
train to recognize their own
symptoms of a lack of oxygen.

37:40.167 --> 37:42.367
Of hypoxia.

37:42.803 --> 37:45.270
In my case,
there's a slight dizziness.

37:46.006 --> 37:48.373
My vision starts to get
a little bit narrow.

37:48.675 --> 37:51.843
The colors become
a little more brittle,

37:52.613 --> 37:54.846
like maybe a certain
type of painter's way

37:54.948 --> 37:57.582
of using only the
primary colors.

37:57.684 --> 37:59.751
Sound changes a little for me.

37:59.853 --> 38:04.456
It becomes a little bit
more staccato, sort of a
snappy sound to everything

38:05.159 --> 38:06.591
that's going on around me.

38:06.693 --> 38:08.560
And as soon as I put all
those things together,

38:08.662 --> 38:11.062
I realize I'm running
out of oxygen.

38:12.299 --> 38:14.099
Houston, I'm having a
serious problem here.

38:14.201 --> 38:15.400
Serious problem.

38:15.502 --> 38:16.802
Blinded in both eyes.

38:16.904 --> 38:18.103
"What did he just say?"

38:18.205 --> 38:20.639
Can't see, purge your oxygen.

38:20.741 --> 38:23.308
My precious oxygen.

38:24.044 --> 38:29.481
I wasn't really sure how that
was gonna turn out, but as
the oxygen hissed through and

38:30.484 --> 38:34.920
out my purge valve,
the tears that were coming
out of my tear ducts

38:35.989 --> 38:38.857
slowly started evaporating.

38:39.493 --> 38:44.196
My vision began to return,
bit by bit, and what had
caused it was pretty simple.

38:45.032 --> 38:50.602
It was the anti-fog on my
visor had been picked up by
floating water in my suit and

38:51.004 --> 38:53.538
gotten into my eye.

38:54.441 --> 38:59.578
With confidence, I could
reach up and close the
valve and stop venting my

38:59.680 --> 39:02.347
precious oxygen out to
the rest of the universe.

39:07.888 --> 39:14.059
It's vital that we get
enough oxygen; but too much
can be just as dangerous.

39:27.975 --> 39:30.775
You see it when you blow
on a little tiny fire.

39:33.046 --> 39:37.916
Just blowing that little
bit of oxygen turns that
tiny spark into a flame.

39:43.257 --> 39:47.325
And it's exactly the same
for the whole planet.

39:50.931 --> 39:54.399
A rise in oxygen levels
can threaten life on Earth.

40:02.276 --> 40:05.944
WILL SMITH: 300 million years
ago, there was a lot more
oxygen in the atmosphere.

40:06.847 --> 40:10.849
So much that the
planet just burned.

40:14.655 --> 40:18.189
But don't think that
danger's all in the past.

40:20.360 --> 40:23.795
Too much oxygen and we fry.

40:25.666 --> 40:28.266
Too little and we choke.

40:29.636 --> 40:33.271
We're walking a tightrope
with death on either side,

40:34.274 --> 40:35.874
and just like a tightrope walker

40:35.976 --> 40:38.843
the only thing that can
save us is balance.

40:50.008 --> 40:52.342
CHRIS: Balance is crucial...

40:54.746 --> 40:57.714
For the makeup of
the atmosphere, and
for life itself.

41:02.187 --> 41:06.056
The thing is, we don't
fully understand how
the Earth manages it.

41:08.393 --> 41:13.964
Despite diatoms having
to wait for glaciers and
South American trees having

41:14.766 --> 41:16.833
to wait for African dust,

41:16.935 --> 41:21.771
and despite the fact
that human population has
been steadily increasing,

41:21.873 --> 41:26.543
the relative amount of
oxygen in the atmosphere has
been surprisingly constant.

41:30.449 --> 41:35.919
MIKE: For millions of
years, oxygen has made up
20.95% of our atmosphere.

41:37.255 --> 41:40.957
MAE: Exactly 20.95%.

41:42.794 --> 41:48.131
JERRY: Everything's somehow
buffering out and keeping
things pretty darn stable.

41:57.776 --> 42:03.980
♪ ♪

42:13.658 --> 42:19.129
♪ ♪

42:31.610 --> 42:37.647
(chanting inaudibly)

43:08.046 --> 43:13.383
WILL SMITH: 100,000
Buddhists gather here for
the festival of Magha Puja.

43:19.558 --> 43:22.725
Each one lights a candle.

43:22.994 --> 43:27.230
They celebrate with their
flames at a temple made
from a million Buddha's.

43:44.349 --> 43:50.120
(chanting inaudibly)

43:58.930 --> 44:05.301
♪ ♪

44:33.231 --> 44:36.833
WILL SMITH: Every breath we
take, 16 breaths a minute,

44:39.738 --> 44:42.639
23,000 breaths a day,

44:42.741 --> 44:48.444
every inhale, every exhale
of that precious oxygen

44:49.648 --> 44:56.019
couldn't happen without
earth, water, wind and fire.

45:07.032 --> 45:12.468
The whole planet works as one
to create that thin blue line.

45:17.609 --> 45:22.612
The mark of a living
world we've seen nowhere
else in the universe.

45:32.324 --> 45:35.558
-I really wish that
everyone could see the
world the way that I've

45:35.961 --> 45:38.962
had a chance to see it.

45:43.134 --> 45:47.570
You have to wrench yourself
away from the wonder
and the strangeness of it.

45:53.144 --> 45:56.412
And the beauty of space
flight is you come back

45:56.514 --> 46:00.717
with a real sense that
this Earth is one place.

46:01.987 --> 46:04.420
One shared place.

46:08.059 --> 46:11.327
We're all crew mates
on the same ship.

46:17.068 --> 46:23.373
WILL SMITH: We're not just
rare, we're not just special,
we are unique and that's what

46:24.075 --> 46:27.577
makes this One Strange Rock.

46:37.389 --> 46:40.023
Next time on One
Strange Rock...

46:40.425 --> 46:44.694
Our paradise planet came from
collisions, carnage and chaos.

46:45.697 --> 46:48.598
And the impact is
still shaping us.

46:58.243 --> 47:00.543
